Below is a **clear, side‑by‑side explanation of Access Token vs ID Token**, written the way it’s expected in **real projects, interviews, and Okta / OAuth discussions**.

***

# ✅ Access Token vs ID Token (OAuth / OIDC)

## 🧠 One‑line difference (remember this)

> **Access Token = “What can you do?”**  
> **ID Token = “Who are you?”**

***

## ✅ What is an **Access Token**?

### 🔹 Definition

> An **Access Token** is used by an application to **access protected APIs** on behalf of a user.

It answers the question:

> **“Is this request allowed?”**

***

### ✅ Who uses it?

*   ✅ Backend APIs
*   ✅ Resource servers
*   ❌ NOT for frontend user identity

***

### ✅ What it contains (claims)

Typical Access Token payload:

```json
{
  "iss": "https://okta.example.com",
  "aud": "api://default",
  "sub": "00u123abc",
  "scope": "read:profile write:order",
  "exp": 1713264000
}
```

✅ Scopes  
✅ Permissions  
✅ Expiration  
✅ Audience (API)

***

### ✅ Where it is sent

```http
Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
```

✅ Every API request  
✅ Validated by backend

***

### ✅ Key rules for Access Tokens

✔ Sent to backend APIs  
✔ Validated by servers  
✔ Contains **authorization data**  
❌ Frontend should not parse or rely on it  
❌ Not meant for UI logic

***

## ✅ What is an **ID Token**?

### 🔹 Definition

> An **ID Token** is used by the frontend to **identify the authenticated user**.

It answers the question:

> **“Who is the user?”**

***

### ✅ Who uses it?

*   ✅ Frontend (React, Next.js)
*   ❌ Backend APIs (usually)

***

### ✅ What it contains (claims)

Typical ID Token payload:

```json
{
  "iss": "https://okta.example.com",
  "sub": "00u123abc",
  "email": "user@example.com",
  "name": "John Doe",
  "picture": "https://..."
}
```

✅ User identity  
✅ Profile info  
✅ Authentication proof

***

### ✅ Where it is used

*   Display username
*   Show profile picture
*   Session context
*   Client‑side auth state

✅ **Never sent to APIs**

***

### ✅ Key rules for ID Tokens

✔ Used only by frontend  
✔ Proves user identity  
✔ Comes from **OpenID Connect (OIDC)**  
❌ No permissions or scopes for APIs  
❌ Not for backend access

***

## 🔁 OAuth + OIDC Flow (Where tokens come from)

```text
User logs in →
Identity Provider (Okta) →
Issues:
✅ ID Token (identity)
✅ Access Token (API access)
```

Both tokens are usually JWTs, but their **purpose is different**.

***

## 🆚 Side‑by‑Side Comparison

| Feature         | Access Token         | ID Token          |
| --------------- | -------------------- | ----------------- |
| Purpose         | Authorization        | Authentication    |
| Answers         | “Can I access this?” | “Who are you?”    |
| Used by         | Backend APIs         | Frontend app      |
| Contains        | Scopes, permissions  | User profile info |
| Sent in request | ✅ Yes                | ❌ No              |
| OAuth / OIDC    | OAuth 2.0            | OpenID Connect    |
| Audience        | API                  | Client app        |

***

## ✅ Real‑world Example (Okta + React)

### 🔐 Login flow

1.  User logs in via Okta
2.  Okta returns **ID token + Access token**

***

### ✅ Frontend usage

```ts
const user = jwtDecode(idToken);
console.log(user.email);
```

✅ Use ID token for UI

***

### ✅ Backend usage

```http
Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
```

✅ Backend validates access token
✅ Checks scopes & permissions

***

## ❌ Common mistakes (VERY important)

### ❌ Using ID Token to call APIs

```http
Authorization: Bearer <id_token> ❌
```

🚫 APIs reject it  
🚫 Security risk

***

### ❌ Parsing access token in frontend UI

```ts
jwtDecode(accessToken).email ❌
```

🚫 Token not meant for UI  
🚫 Claims may change

***

## ✅ Best‑practice summary ✅

| Task                  | Use          |
| --------------------- | ------------ |
| Display user name     | ID Token     |
| Protect API endpoints | Access Token |
| UI auth state         | ID Token     |
| API authorization     | Access Token |

***

## 🧠 Interview‑ready explanations ✅

**Access Token**

> “An access token is used by clients to access protected backend APIs and contains authorization information such as scopes and permissions.”

**ID Token**

> “An ID token is used by the client application to identify the authenticated user and contains user profile information.”

**Difference**

> “Access tokens are for APIs, ID tokens are for the application UI.”

***

## ✅ Diagram (mental model)

    Frontend (React)
      ├── uses ID Token → UI / User info
      └── sends Access Token → Backend API

    Backend API
      └── validates Access Token only

***

## ✅ Final takeaway (one line)

> **ID Tokens authenticate users; Access Tokens authorize API access. Mixing them is a security bug.**

